s objects of affection have clear roots in eighteenth- and nineteenth-century publishing, reading habits, and domestic history. While never denying the very real feelings that warm our relationship to books, Loving Literature nonetheless serves as a riposte to those who use the phrase “the love of literature” as if its meaning were transparent. Lynch writes, “It is as if those on the side of love of literature had forgotten what literary texts themselves say about love’s edginess and complexities.” With this masterly volume, Lynch restores those edges and allows us to revel in those complexities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexAppreciationxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aEnglish literaturexAppreciation. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aliterature, academia, faculty, scholarship, joy, pleasure, graduate school, scholars, affect theory, publishing, reading habits, book lovers, domesticity, history, nonfiction, canon, poetry, classics, authorship, emotions, appreciation, books, friendship, connection, sentimentality, identity, childhood, affection, experience, reader response, feelings, antiquarianism, mourning, perversion, sexuality, gender, attachment, cultural capital, marketplace, commercialism, capitalism, mass production.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022618370140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226183848423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226183848/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles